.TH XPAR 1
.SH NAME
xpar \- an error/erasure code system guarding data integrity
.SH SYNOPSIS
.ll +8
.B xpar
.RB [ " \-Je " / " \-Jd " ]
.RB [ " \-hfvqVc " ]
.RB [ " \-i/--interlacing\ # " ]
.RB [ " \-H/--integrity=<algo> " ]
.RB [ " \--auth=<keyfile> " ]
.RB [ " \--no-mmap\ " ]
[
.I "names \&..."
]
.ll -8
.br
.B xpar
.RB [ " \-Jse " / " \-Jsd " ]
.RB [ " \-hfvqVc " ]
.RB [ " \--no-mmap\ " ]
[
.I "names \&..."
]
.br
.B xpar
.RB [ " \-We " / " \-Le " ]
.RB [ " \-hfvqV " ]
.RB [ " \--out-prefix\ # ", " \--dshards\ # ", " \--pshards\ # " ]
.RB [ " \-H/--integrity=<algo> " ]
.RB [ " \--auth=<keyfile> " ]
.RB [ " \--no-mmap\ " ]
[
.I "names \&..."
]
.br
.B xpar
.RB [ " \-Wd " / " \-Ld " / " \-Wt " / " \-Lt " ]
.RB [ " \-hfvqV " ]
.RB [ " \--auth=<keyfile> " ]
[
.I "names \&..."
]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
The
.B xpar
command
is the command-line interface to an error/erasure code system which
fortifies data and corrects errors in the data or reconstructs missing
shards.
.PP
.B xpar
in joint encoding mode (
.B \-Je
) generates a slightly inflated (by about 12%) parity-guarded
file from a given data file with the extension
.I .xpar
. Such a file can be recovered as long as no more than about 6.2% of the
data is corrupted. xpar internally uses a (255,223)-RS code over an 8-bit
Galois field. At most two filenames intertwined with flags are expected
as arguments.
.B xpar
will by default not overwrite existing files. If this behaviour is intended,
use the
.B \-f
option.
If no file names are specified,
.B xpar
will process data from the standard input and write it to the standard output,
refusing to output binary data to a terminal. If two files are specified,
the first one is used in place of standard input, and the second one is used
in place of standard output. If the -c flag is present,
.B xpar
will read from the specified file and output data to standard output instead.
Otherwise, if decoding, 
.B xpar
will try to guess the decompressed filename by removing the
.I .xpar
extension. If not present, an error will be reported. If encoding
the output filename will be generated by appending the
.I .xpar
extension to the input filename.
.PP
In joint mode, the flag
.B \-i/\-\-interlacing
can be used to specify the interlacing factor. This does not affect the
nominal error correction capability (in the sense of a noisy memory-less
channel model), but can be used to increase the robustness against burst
errors. The default interlacing factor is 1 and the maximum correctible burst
error length is 16 (as given by the Singleton bound). The interlacing factor
of 2 transposes 65025-byte blocks of data and hence can correct burst errors
of length 4080. The interlacing factor of 3 transposes approx. 16MB blocks of
data and can correct burst errors of length approx. 1MB. In theory, with the
interlacing factor of one, up to 32 burst errors could be corrected - this
problem is however NP-hard and reduces to polynomial reconstruction (the basis
of e.g. Shamir's secret sharing scheme). As an added benefit, higher
interlacing factors tend to result in faster processing (up to 50%) as the
workload is more parallelisable.
.PP
The joint\-mode flag
.B \-s/\-\-systematic
switches to a systematic output layout. The encoder writes only the 32
parity bytes per 223-byte input block (plus an 8-byte block header) into
the
.I .xpa
file; the original data file is not copied and remains on disk under its
original name, directly accessible without any decoding step. The
.I .xpa
is consequently around 18% of the input size rather than 114%. On decode,
.B xpar
reads the (possibly corrupted) original as the first positional argument
and the parity
.I .xpa
as the second (inferred as
.I original.xpa
when only one argument is given), and writes the corrected data to
standard output. Systematic mode is incompatible with
.BR \-\-interlacing :
each 223-byte block is handled independently and can correct up to 16
byte errors. A file produced with
.B \-s
cannot be decoded without
.BR \-s ,
and vice versa;
.B xpar
detects the mismatch and refuses with a clear error.
.PP
The joint\-mode file format binds each lace to its position via a
sequence number in the block header and records the total input size in
the file header. Truncation at a lace boundary and lace reordering are
both detected on decode and rejected with a clear error. By default, the
per-lace integrity tag is a 32-bit CRC32C. The
.B \-H/\-\-integrity
flag selects the tag algorithm:
.B crc32c
(default) or
.B blake2b
(128-bit BLAKE2b tag, giving 2\[ha]64 birthday-bound collision resistance
instead of CRC32C's 2\[ha]16). BLAKE2b mode grows the per-lace block
header from 12 to 24 bytes; at interlacing factor 1 this raises the
.I .xpa
overhead from ~18% to ~24%; at factors 2 and 3 the change is
negligible (one header per 65 kB or 16 MB respectively).
.PP
The
.B \-H/\-\-integrity
flag picks the per-lace / per-shard integrity tag: the default
.B crc32c
is a 32-bit hardware-accelerated CRC, and
.B blake2b
produces an unkeyed 128-bit BLAKE2b hash instead. In sharded modes
this grows each shard header from 20 to 32 bytes.
.PP
The
.B \-\-auth=<keyfile>
flag reads a 1\(en64-byte key from
.I keyfile
and switches the integrity tag to a keyed BLAKE2b-128 MAC. It implies
.BR "\-H blake2b" .
An encode with
.B \-\-auth
can only be decoded with the same key; decoders presented with the
wrong key, no key, or an extra key against a non-keyed file all refuse.
Keep the key file outside the
.I .xpa
(xpar never embeds it). All three modes (CRC32C, BLAKE2b hash, BLAKE2b
MAC) are supported in both joint and sharded modes, selected by the
version byte of the file/shard header so decoders auto-detect.
.PP
The v1.0 file format is incompatible with v0.x tools: magic bytes and
header fields moved, and a version check in the decoder rejects older
archives. Re-encode anything you still need.
.PP
The sharded modes' per-shard header also changed at v1.0. The integrity
tag (CRC32C, BLAKE2b hash, or BLAKE2b MAC) now covers the full header
(version byte, shard count, shard number, total size) as well as the
shard body, so a
.I shard_number
bit-flip or a header-field swap between shards is detected.
.PP
.B xpar
in sharded encoding mode (
.B \-We
or
.B \-Le
) generates a set of parity-guarded files from a given data file. The amount
of files generated is given by the sum of the mandatory parameters
.B \--dshards
and
.B \--pshards
- which specify the number of data and parity shards, respectively. The data
shards contain the file contents verbatim (
.B xpar\ 
uses a systematic code). The data is reconstructible as long as there are more
than
.B \--dshards
shards available.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-W --van-sharded
Enable sharded processing mode using Vandermonde matrices in O(n^3) via the
Berlekamp-Welch algorithm. Slowest sharded mode, parallelisable.
.B \-L --fft-sharded
Enable sharded processing mode using FFT in O(n log n) via the Leopard
algorithm. Fastest sharded mode.
.TP
.B \-J --joint
Enable joint processing mode.
.TP
.B \-e --encode
Enable encoding mode.
.TP
.B \-d --decode
Enable decoding mode.
.TP
.B \-t --test
Enable integrity-check mode. Reads the same inputs as
.B \-d
and writes no output; exits non-zero if the input cannot be recovered.
For joint mode, runs the full error-correction pipeline and reports any
unrecoverable block or CRC mismatch. For sharded mode, validates each
shard's header and CRC and verifies that enough valid shards remain to
reconstruct the original. Works with
.BR \-J ,
.BR \-Js ,
.BR \-W ,
and
.BR \-L .
.TP
.B \-h --help
Print a help message and exit.
.TP
.B \-f --force
Force operation. Ignore errors and try to recover from them, if possible.
Overwrite existing files.
.TP
.B \-v --verbose
Be verbose. Print additional information.
.TP
.B \-q --quiet
Be quiet. Suppress most output, except fatal errors.
.TP
.B \-V --version
Print version information of the package and exit.
.TP
.B \-c --stdout
Write resultant data to standard output. Joint mode only.
.TP
.B \-i --interlacing
Specify the interlacing factor. Joint mode only.
.TP
.B \-s --systematic
Joint mode only. Write a parity-only
.I .xpa
file that does not contain the original data; pair with
.B \-e
to encode. On decode, pass the (possibly corrupted) original and the
parity
.I .xpa
as positional arguments; corrected data is written to standard output.
Incompatible with
.BR \-\-interlacing .
.TP
.B \-H --integrity=<algo>
Joint mode only. Selects the per-lace integrity algorithm:
.B crc32c
(default, 32-bit hardware-accelerated CRC) or
.B blake2b
(128-bit BLAKE2b tag). BLAKE2b gives stronger collision resistance at a
modest encode-time throughput cost and a larger per-lace block-header
footprint.
.TP
.B \--auth=<keyfile>
Joint mode only. Reads a 1\(en64-byte key from
.I keyfile
and enables keyed-MAC mode (implies
.BR "\-H blake2b" ).
Encode writes a keyed BLAKE2b tag per lace; decode requires the same
key and rejects any mismatch.
.TP
.B \--no-mmap
Disable memory mapping. Generally results in worse performance, as the
fallback method is to read the file in chunks using the standard I/O library.
.TP
.B \-j --jobs
Specify the amount of CPU cores to use. Not setting this value or setting it
to zero will result in the program automatically deciding the amount of cores
to use. Setting it to one will disable parallel processing.
.TP
.B \--out-prefix
Specify the prefix for the output files (shards). Sharded mode only.
.TP
.B \--dshards
Specify the number of data shards. Sharded mode only. Mandatory.
.TP
.B \--pshards
Specify the number of parity shards. Sharded mode only. Mandatory.
